margin-right: 0.1389em;">F</span></span></span></span></code> is the distri=
bution function.
</p>
<p>In <code>rhyper()</code>, if one of <code class=3D"reqn"><span class=3D"=
katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/M=
ath/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo separator=3D"true">,</mo><mi>n</=
mi><mo separator=3D"true">,</mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-tex">m, n, k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=
=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"st=
rut" style=3D"height: 0.8889em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span cl=
ass=3D"mord mathnormal">m</span><span class=3D"mpunct">,</span><span class=
=3D"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class=3D"mord ma=
thnormal">n</span><span class=3D"mpunct">,</span><span class=3D"mspace" sty=
le=3D"margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class=3D"mord mathnormal" style=
=3D"margin-right: 0.0315em;">k</span></span></span></span></code> exceeds <=
code><a href=3D"https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/base/html/zMa=
chine.html">.Machine</a>$integer.max</code>,
currently the equivalent of <code>qhyper(runif(nn), m,n,k)</code> is used
which is comparably slow while instead a binomial approximation may be
considerably more efficient.
</p>


<h3>Value</h3>

<p><code>dhyper</code> gives the density,
<code>phyper</code> is the cumulative distribution function, and
<code>qhyper</code> is the quantile function of the hypergeometric distribu=
tion.
<code>rhyper</code> generates random deviates.
</p>
<p>Invalid arguments will result in return value <code>NaN</code>, with a w=
arning.
</p>
<p>The length of the result is determined by <code>n</code> for
<code>rhyper</code>, and is the maximum of the lengths of the
numerical arguments for the other functions.
</p>
<p>The numerical arguments other than <code>n</code> are recycled to the
length of the result.  Only the first elements of the logical
arguments are used.
</p>


<h3>Source</h3>

<p><code>dhyper</code> computes via binomial probabilities, using code
contributed by Catherine Loader (see <code><a href=3D"https://stat.ethz.ch/=
R-manual/R-devel/library/stats/help/dbinom.html">dbinom</a></code>).
</p>
<p><code>phyper</code> is based on calculating <code>dhyper</code> and
<code>phyper(...)/dhyper(...)</code> (as a summation), based on ideas of Ia=
n
Smith and Morten Welinder.
</p>
<p><code>qhyper</code> is based on inversion (of an earlier <code>phyper()<=
/code> algorithm).
</p>
<p><code>rhyper</code> is based on a corrected version of
=E2=81=A0<a href=3D"https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/stats/htm=
l/Hypergeometric.html#reference+Hypergeometric.Rd+R+3AKachitvichyanukul+2BS=
chmeiser+3A1985"><span class=3D"citation">Kachitvichyanukul and Schmeiser (=
1985)</span></a>.
</p>


<h3>References</h3>

<p>=E2=81=A0<span id=3D"reference+Hypergeometric.Rd+R+3AJohnson+2BKotz+2BKe=
mp+3A1993">Johnson NL, Kotz S, Kemp AW (1993).
<em>Continuous Univariate Distributions</em>.
Wiley, New York.
ISBN 978-0471548973.</span>
</p>
<p>=E2=81=A0<span id=3D"reference+Hypergeometric.Rd+R+3AKachitvichyanukul+2=
BSchmeiser+3A1985">Kachitvichyanukul V, Schmeiser BW (1985).
=E2=80=9CComputer Generation of Hypergeometric Random Variates.=E2=80=9D
<em>Journal of Statistical Computation and Simulation</em>, <b>22</b>(2), 1=
27=E2=80=93145.
<a href=3D"https://doi.org/10.1080/00949658508810839">doi:10.1080/009496585=
08810839</a>.</span>
</p>


<h3>See Also</h3>

<p><a href=3D"https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/stats/help/Dist=
ributions.html">Distributions</a> for other standard distributions.
</p>


<h3>Examples</h3>

<pre><code class=3D"language-R">m &lt;- 10; n &lt;- 7; k &lt;- 8
x &lt;- 0:(k+1)
rbind(phyper(x, m, n, k), dhyper(x, m, n, k))
all(phyper(x, m, n, k) =3D=3D cumsum(dhyper(x, m, n, k)))  # FALSE
## but errors are very small:
signif(phyper(x, m, n, k) - cumsum(dhyper(x, m, n, k)), digits =3D 3)

stopifnot(abs(phyper(x, m, n, k) - cumsum(dhyper(x, m, n, k))) &lt; 5e-16)
</code></pre>

